{#
  Example 01 — Basic usage.

  The minimum viable select: a label, a themes directory, and a slug
  list. The client.js resolves "light" as the initial active theme
  (since "light" is in the list), sets data-theme="light" on <html>,
  and injects a <link rel="stylesheet"> pointing at
  /assets/themes/light.css.

  Drop the macro file alongside this one, the client.js next to that,
  and load the script tag at the bottom. The script is not optional:
  the macro renders an icon button plus a hidden listbox, and the
  button does not open until the client.js runs. See ../docs/ssr.md.

  Note the status region below the control. The trigger is an
  icon-only button, so it never displays the active theme, and a
  screen-reader user hears the active theme only after opening the
  listbox. The status line is part of the default pattern — see
  ../docs/accessibility.md. Omitting it is the deliberate choice.
#}
{% from "../theme-chooser.njk" import themeChooser %}

{{ themeChooser({
    label: "Theme",
    themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
    themes: ["light", "dark", "abyss"]
}) }}

{#
  Visible by default: it helps sighted users and cognitive
  accessibility too, and WCAG 2.2 AAA favours it. For designs that
  cannot spare the space, make it visually hidden instead of dropping
  it — recipe in ../docs/styling.md.

  aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this region is
  silent on first paint and speaks on each subsequent change. That is
  the intended behaviour.
#}
<p class="theme-chooser-status" aria-live="polite"></p>

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit } from "../theme-chooser.client.js";

    // Show the human label, not the raw slug. These strings are
    // consumer-supplied and translatable — the helper never hardcodes
    // user-facing text.
    const THEME_LABELS = { light: "Light", dark: "Dark", abyss: "Abyss" };
    const status = document.querySelector(".theme-chooser-status");

    autoInit({
        onChange(slug) {
            status.textContent = `Active theme: ${THEME_LABELS[slug] ?? slug}`;
        },
    });
</script>
